│                                                                                            │
│   bool match(CmpInst *Cmp) {                                                               │
│     if (Cmp->getPredicate() != Pred) // It is compared here.                               │
│       return false;                                                                        │
│     // ...                                                                                 │
│   }                                                                                        │
│ };                                                                                         │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ The problem is that this struct has no constructor to initialize the `Pred` member. In     │
│ C++, if a class/struct has no user-defined constructor, its members with primitive types   │
│ (like the integer-based `Pred_t` for `CmpInst::Predicate`) are left uninitialized.         │
│                                                                                            │
│ When `foldShuffleOfBinops` calls `m_SpecificCmp(Pred, ...)` where `Pred` was captured from │
│ the first `icmp`, the `CmpPattern` object is created, but its internal `Pred` member holds │
│ an indeterminate (garbage) value. The subsequent comparison `Cmp->getPredicate() != Pred`  │
│ is therefore unreliable. In this specific case, it happens to evaluate to `false`,         │
│ allowing the match to succeed incorrectly and causing the mis-compilation.                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to add a constructor to the `CmpPattern` specialization to properly initialize  │
│ the `Pred` member.                                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to add a constructor to `CmpPattern<Pred_t, true>` that initializes the `Pred`  │
│ member. This ensures that when `m_SpecificCmp(Pred, ...)` is used, the pattern object is   │
│ constructed with the correct predicate value, making the subsequent `match` operation      │
│ reliable.                                                                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ **File**: `llvm/include/llvm/IR/PatternMatch.h`                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ template <typename Pred_t>                                                                 │
│ struct CmpPattern<Pred_t, true /* Specific */> {                                           │
│   Pred_t Pred;                                                                             │
│   CmpPattern(Pred_t Pred) : Pred(Pred) {}                                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│   bool match(CmpInst *Cmp) {                                                               │
│     if (Cmp->getPredicate() != Pred)                                                       │
│       return false;                                                                        │
│     return true;                                                                           │
│   }                                                                                        │
│ };                                                                                         │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The bug is a classic case of an uninitialized member variable in a C++ template class used │
│ for pattern matching. The proposed one-line fix initializes this member in a new           │
│ constructor, correcting the behavior of the `m_SpecificCmp` matcher. With this fix, the    │
│ `foldShuffleOfBinops` transformation will correctly reject cases where the `icmp`          │
│ predicates do not match, preventing this and similar mis-compilations.                     │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                            │
